A calibrationCalibration is a procedure to convert the GCGas Chromatograph (GC) output into a concentration unit, typically parts per million (ppm) or parts per billion (ppb). To develop a calibrationCalibration curve (Fig. 2.5), normally three to four gas standardsStandard of known concentration are injected into a GCGas Chromatograph (GC) and analysed. StandardStandard gas containing gas mixtures at increasing concentrations, contained in gas cylinders, can be ordered from commercial gas companies. With increasing gas concentrations, the GCGas Chromatograph (GC) output also increases. Either a linear increase (e.g. for CH4Methane (CH4)) or a non-linear (CO2Carbon dioxide (CO2)and N2ONitrous oxide (N2O)) increase is observed which can be described by the following equations (Eqs. 2.1 and 2.2). Note, if the increase is linear, the term “a” in Eq. 2.2 is zero and the entire equation is reduced to a linear regressionLinear regression.Fig. 2.5
