The approach taken in the second phase of inventory development for determining N2ONitrous oxide (N2O) emissions from agricultural soils was to include direct emissions from agricultural fields, direct emissions from animal production systems, and indirect emissionsIndirect emission. Indirect emissionsIndirect emission result from volatilisationVolatilization and subsequent depositionDepositionof NH3Ammonia (NH3) and NOx, leachingLeaching and runoff of N, and human consumption of crops followed by sewage treatment. NitrogenNitrogen (N)leachingLeaching and runoff from agricultural systems (NLEACHNLEACH) include N applied as fertiliser (NFERT; kg N year−1), and N derived from animal excretion (NEX; kg N year−1) so that manure produced during grazing is captured. The fraction of fertiliser and excreta N that moves through the leachingLeaching and runoff pathways (FRACLEACH) was estimated by Mosier et al. (1998) to range from 0.1 to 0.8. Some countries have developed country-specific values for FRACLEACH (Thomas et al. 2005). Thus, the flux of N leached (NLEACHNLEACH, kg N year−1) (Eq. 2.13) is2.13NLEACH=[NFERT + NEX]×FRACLEACH\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
