Numerous modelsModelexistWaterin theNitrous oxide (N2O) literature for estimating k, and it is beyond the scope of this section to cover all of these. However, N2ONitrous oxide (N2O) emissions from agricultural drainsAgricultural drains and first-order streamsStream are recognised hotspots for N2ONitrous oxide (N2O) emissions (Reay et al. 2003; Beaulieu et al. 2008; Outram and Hiscock 2012; Turner et al. 2015; Davis and David 2018), and these sites readily allow the collection of variables required for modelling. One model which has been used extensively is that of O’Connor and Dobbins (1958) who introduced the modelModel to predict k based on waterWater turbulence (Eq. 2.32):2.32k=DUh0.5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ k = \left( {\frac{DU}{h}} \right)^{0.5} $$\end{document}where U is the streamStream velocity (m s−1), h is the average riverRiver depth (m), and D (m2 s−1) is the diffusion coefficient of the respective gas in waterWater at the water’sWatergiven temperatureTemperature regulation, temperature. This modelModel has been widely used. More recently, in a meta-analysis of 563 direct gas tracer release experiments, Raymond et al. (2012) found that the gas transfer velocityGas transfer velocity scaled with the product of streamStream slope and velocity, and they reported further models for estimating k and Schmidt numbers in streams. Other models (e.g. Schwarzenbach et al. 1993) have also been used to determine k by partitioning the individual contributions of waterWater and wind-driven turbulence effects (Beaulieu et al. 2012; Hamma-Aziz et al. 2016).

